parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The intermittent brake failure can cause the vehicle to lose braking power, leading to accidents or near-misses, and potentially resulting in injuries or fatalities.
symptoms: The brake pedal becomes soft or spongy
the brake pedal drops to the floor
the brake light illuminates on the dashboard
grinding or pulsing noise when applying the brakes
and loss of braking capacity.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: An inaccurate fuel gauge reading can cause the vehicle to run out of fuel without warning, leading to sudden stalling, loss of power steering and power brakes, and increased risk of accidents.
symptoms: The fuel gauge displays an incorrect fuel level
typically showing a quarter tank or more remaining when the tank is actually empty
the vehicle stalls or runs out of fuel without warning
the fuel gauge displays a full reading when the tank is nearly empty.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Failure of the fuel sending unit can cause the fuel gauge to malfunction, leading to inaccurate fuel level readings, sudden stalling, and increased risk of accidents.
symptoms: The fuel gauge displays an incorrect fuel level
the vehicle stalls or runs out of fuel without warning
the fuel gauge displays a full reading when the tank is nearly empty.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: Transmission or fuel-related problems can cause the vehicle to stall or hesitate, leading to loss of power and increased risk of accidents.
symptoms: The vehicle stalls or hesitates
the vehicle holds briefly before moving
the transmission or fuel system malfunctions.

parsedComplaintsResult.impact: The failure of the fuel gauge can cause the vehicle to run out of fuel without warning, leading to sudden stalls, accidents, and potentially life-threatening situations.
symptoms: The fuel gauge shows incorrect readings
the vehicle stalls without warning
the fuel gauge stops working at a certain level (e.g.
half a tank)
the vehicle runs out of fuel despite the gauge showing available fuel
the vehicle experiences sudden loss of power.
